":\\\"Organization\\\",\\\"name\\\":\\\"AlgoForge\\\"},\\\"publisher\\\":{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"Organization\\\",\\\"name\\\":\\\"AlgoForge\\\"},\\\"datePublished\\\":\\\"2026-01-01\\\",\\\"dateModified\\\":\\\"2026-07-17\\\"}\"}}],[\"$\",\"script\",null,{\"type\":\"application/ld+json\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"$1d\"}}],[\"$\",\"script\",null,{\"type\":\"application/ld+json\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"{\\\"@context\\\":\\\"https://schema.org\\\",\\\"@type\\\":\\\"HowTo\\\",\\\"name\\\":\\\"How to solve Minimum Time For K Virus Variants to Spread\\\",\\\"description\\\":\\\"Original Hard explanation for Minimum Time For K Virus Variants to Spread (LeetCode #1956). Pattern: binary search. Time O(nlogn * logr), space O(n). Multi-language solutions and interview tips.\\\",\\\"step\\\":[{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"HowToStep\\\",\\\"position\\\":1,\\\"text\\\":\\\"Read the official problem statement on LeetCode\\\"},{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"HowToStep\\\",\\\"position\\\":2,\\\"text\\\":\\\"Solve on paper / whiteboard first\\\"},{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"HowToStep\\\",\\\"position\\\":3,\\\"text\\\":\\\"Implement the binary search and segment tree approach\\\"},{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"HowToStep\\\",\\\"position\\\":4,\\\"text\\\":\\\"Verify edge cases from the checklist\\\"},{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"HowToStep\\\",\\\"position\\\":5,\\\"text\\\":\\\"State time and space complexity aloud\\\"},{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"HowToStep\\\",\\\"position\\\":6,\\\"text\\\":\\\"Compare with the AlgoForge reference solution\\\"},{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"HowToStep\\\",\\\"position\\\":7,\\\"text\\\":\\\"Schedule a revision session\\\"}]}\"}}],[\"$\",\"nav\",null,{\"aria-label\":\"Breadcrumb\",\"className\":\"text-sm text-muted-foreground\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"script\",null,{\"type\":\"application/ld+json\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"{\\\"@context\\\":\\\"https://schema.org\\\",\\\"@type\\\":\\\"BreadcrumbList\\\",\\\"itemListElement\\\":[{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"ListItem\\\",\\\"position\\\":1,\\\"name\\\":\\\"Home\\\",\\\"item\\\":\\\"https://algoforge.dev/\\\"},{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"ListItem\\\",\\\"position\\\":2,\\\"name\\\":\\\"Problems\\\",\\\"item\\\":\\\"https://algoforge.dev/problems\\\"},{\\\"@type\\\":\\\"ListItem\\\",\\\"position\\\":3,\\\"name\\\":\\\"Minimum Time For K Virus Variants to Spread\\\",\\\"item\\\":\\\"https://algoforge.dev/problems/minimum-time-for-k-virus-variants-to-spread\\\"}]}\"}}],\"$L1e\"]}],\"$L1f\"]}]\n20:I[56303,[\"/_next/static/chunks/2fvm6eoqeukxu.js\",\"/_next/static/chunks/1ntn7efqc-iiw.js\",\"/_next/static/chunks/0plpm2axnqe9k.js\",\"/_next/static/chunks/259rkrk9l2f9c.js\"],\"BookmarkButton\"]\n21:I[705747,[\"/_next/static/chunks/2fvm6eoqeukxu.js\",\"/_next/static/chunks/1ntn7efqc-iiw.js\",\"/_next/static/chunks/0plpm2axnqe9k.js\",\"/_next/static/chunks/259rkrk9l2f9c.js\"],\"CodeTabs\"]\n1e:[\"$\",\"ol\",null,{\"className\":\"flex flex-wrap items-center gap-1.5\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"li\",\"/\",{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-1.5\",\"children\":[false,[\"$\",\"$L3\",null,{\"href\":\"/\",\"className\":\"hover:text-primary transition-colors\",\"children\":\"Home\"}]]}],[\"$\",\"li\",\"/problems\",{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-1.5\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"span\",null,{\"aria-hidden\":true,\"className\":\"text-border\",\"children\":\"/\"}],[\"$\",\"$L3\",null,{\"href\":\"/problems\",\"className\":\"hover:text-primary transition-colors\",\"children\":\"Problems\"}]]}],[\"$\",\"li\",\"/problems/minimum-time-for-k-virus-variants-to-spread\",{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-1.5\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"span\",null,{\"aria-hidden\":true,\"className\":\"text-border\",\"children\":\"/\"}],[\"$\",\"span\",null,{\"className\":\"text-foreground font-medium\",\"aria-current\":\"page\",\"children\":\"Minimum Time For K Virus Variants to Spread\"}]]}]]}]\n22:T1b60,// Time:  O(nlogn * logr), r is the sum of range x size and range y size\n// Space: O(n)\n\n// competitive programming solution\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    int minDayskVariants(vector<vector<int>>& points, int k) {\n        std::transform(begin(points), end(points), begin(points),\n                       [](const auto& v) {\n                           return vector<int>({v[0] + v[1], v[0] - v[1]});  // rotate\n                       });\n        const auto& compare_y = [](const vector<int>& a, const vector<int>& b) { return a[1] < b[1]; };\n        const int min_x = (*min_element(cbegin(points), cend(points)))[0];\n        const int max_x = (*max_element(cbegin(points), cend(points)))[0];\n        const int min_y = (*min_element(cbegin(points), cend(points), compare_y))[1];\n        const int max_y = (*max_element(cbegin(points), cend(points), compare_y))[1];\n        int64_t left = 0, right = ((int64_t(max_x) - min_x) + (int64_t(max_y) - min_y) + 1) / 2;\n        while (left <= right) {\n            const auto& mid = left + (right - left) / 2;\n            if (check(points, k, mid)) {\n                right = mid - 1;\n            } else {\n                left = mid + 1;\n            }\n        }\n        return left;                       \n    }\n\nprivate:\n    class SegmentTree {\n    public:\n        SegmentTree(int N)\n            : N_(N),\n              tree_(2 * N),\n              lazy_(N)\n        {\n            H_ = 1;\n            while ((1 << H_) < N) {\n                ++H_;\n            }\n        }\n\n        void update(int L, int R, int h) {\n            L += N_; R += N_;\n            int L0 = L, R0 = R;\n            while (L <= R) {\n                if ((L & 1) == 1) {\n                    apply(L++, h);\n                }\n                if ((R & 1) == 0) {\n                    apply(R--, h);\n                }\n                L >>= 1; R >>= 1;\n            }\n            pull(L0); pull(R0);\n        }\n\n        int query(int L, int R) {\n            L += N_; R += N_;\n            auto result = 0;\n            push(L); push(R);\n            while (L <= R) {\n                if ((L & 1) == 1) {\n                    result = max(result, tree_[L++]);\n                }\n                if ((R & 1) == 0) {\n                    result = max(result, tree_[R--]);\n                }\n                L >>= 1; R >>= 1;\n            }\n            return result;\n        }\n\n    private:\n        int N_, H_;\n        vector<int> tree_, lazy_;\n\n        void apply(int x, int val) {\n            tree_[x] += val;\n            if (x < N_) {\n                lazy_[x] += val;\n            }\n        }\n\n        void pull(int x) {\n            while (x > 1) {\n                x >>= 1;\n                tree_[x] = max(tree_[x * 2], tree_[x * 2 + 1]);\n                if (lazy_[x]) {\n                    tree_[x] += lazy_[x];\n                }\n            }\n        }\n\n        void push(int x) {\n            for (int h = H_; h > 0; --h) {\n                int y = x >> h;\n                if (lazy_[y] != 0) {\n                    apply(y * 2, lazy_[y]);\n                    apply(y * 2 + 1, lazy_[y]);\n                    lazy_[y] = 0;\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    };\n\n    bool check(const vector<vector<int>>& points, int k, int l) {  // Time: O(nlogn), Space: O(n)\n        using Event = tuple<int64_t, int64_t, int64_t, int64_t>;\n        vector<Event> intervals;\n        unordered_set<int64_t> y_set;\n        for (const auto& p : points) {\n            // add [y0, y1] by 1 in [x0, x1+1)\n            int64_t x0 = int64_t(p[0]) - l, y0 = int64_t(p[1]) - l, x1 = int64_t(p[0]) + l, y1 = int64_t(p[1]) + l;\n            intervals.emplace_back(x0    , +1, y0, y1);\n            intervals.emplace_back(x1 + 1, -1, y0, y1);\n            y_set.emplace(y0);\n            y_set.emplace(y1);\n        }\n        sort(begin(intervals), end(intervals));\n        vector<int64_t> sorted_y(cbegin(y_set), cend(y_set));\n        sort(begin(sorted_y), end(sorted_y));\n        unordered_map<int64_t, int> y_to_idx;\n        for (int i = 0; i < size(sorted_y); ++i) {  // coordinate compression\n            y_to_idx[sorted_y[i]] = i;\n        }\n        SegmentTree st(size(y_to_idx));\n        for (const auto& [_, v, y0, y1] : intervals) {  // line sweep\n            st.update(y_to_idx[y0], y_to_idx[y1], v);\n            if (st.query(0, size(y_to_idx) - 1) >= k) {\n                return true;\n            }\n        }\n        return false;\n    }\n};\n\n// Time:  O(n^2 * logr), r is the sum of range x size and range y size\n// Space: O(n)\n// interview solution\nclass Solution2 {\npublic:\n    int minDayskVariants(vector<vector<int>>& points, int k) {\n        std::transform(begin(points), end(points), begin(points),\n                       [](const auto& v) {\n                           return vector<int>({v[0] + v[1], v[0] - v[1]});  // rotate\n                       });\n        const auto& compare_y = [](const vector<int>& a, const vector<int>& b) { return a[1] < b[1]; };\n        const int min_x = (*min_element(cbegin(points), cend(points)))[0];\n        const int max_x = (*max_element(cbegin(points), cend(points)))[0];\n        const int min_y = (*min_element(cbegin(points), cend(points), compare_y))[1];\n        const int max_y = (*max_element(cbegin(points), cend(points), compare_y))[1];\n        int64_t left = 0, right = ((int64_t(max_x) - min_x) + (int64_t(max_y) - min_y) + 1) / 2;\n        while (left <= right) {\n            const auto& mid = left + (right - left) / 2;\n            if (check(points, k, mid)) {\n                right = mid - 1;\n            } else {\n                left = mid + 1;\n            }\n        }\n        return left;                       \n    }\n\nprivate:\n    bool check(const vector<vector<int>>& points, int k, int l) {  // Time: O(n^2), Space: O(n)\n        unordered_map<int64_t, unordered_map<int64_t, int>> intervals;\n        unordered_set<int64_t> y_set;\n        for (const auto& p : points) {\n            // add [y0, y1+1) by 1 in [x0, x1+1)\n            int64_t x0 = int64_t(p[0]) - l, y0 = int64_t(p[1]) - l, x1 = int64_t(p[0]) + l, y1 = int64_t(p[1]) + l;\n            ++intervals[x0][y0];\n            --intervals[x0][y1 + 1];\n            --intervals[x1 + 1][y0];\n            ++intervals[x1 + 1][y1 + 1];\n            y_set.emplace(y0);\n            y_set.emplace(y1 + 1);\n        }\n        vector<int64_t> sorted_x;\n        for (const auto& [x, _] : intervals) {\n            sorted_x.emplace_back(x);\n        }\n        sort(begin(sorted_x), end(sorted_x));\n        vector<int64_t> sorted_y(cbegin(y_set), cend(y_set));\n        sort(begin(sorted_y), end(sorted_y));\n        unordered_map<int64_t, int> count;\n        for (const auto& x : sorted_x) {  // line sweep\n            for (const auto& [y, c] : intervals[x]) {\n                count[y] += c;\n            }\n            int cnt = 0;\n            for (const auto& y : sorted_y) {\n                cnt += count[y];\n                if (cnt >= k) {\n                    return true;\n                }\n            }\n        }\n        return false;\n    }\n};\n23:T1752,# Time:  O(nlogn * logr), r is the sum of range x size and range y size\n# Space: O(n)\n\n# Range Maximum Query\nclass SegmentTree(object):  # 0-based index\n    def __init__(self, N,\n                 build_fn=lambda x, y: [y]*(2*x),\n                 query_fn=lambda x, y: y if x is None else max(x, y),\n                 update_fn=lambda x, y: y if x is None else x+y,\n                 default_val=0):\n        self.N = N\n        self.H = (N-1).bit_length()\n        self.query_fn = query_fn\n        self.update_fn = update_fn\n        self.default_val = default_val\n        self.tree = build_fn(N, default_val)\n        self.lazy = [None]*N\n\n    def __apply(self, x, val):\n        self.tree[x] = self.update_fn(self.tree[x], val)\n        if x < self.N:\n            self.lazy[x] = self.update_fn(self.lazy[x], val)\n\n    def update(self, L, R, h):  # Time: O(logN), Space: O(N)\n        def pull(x):\n            while x > 1:\n                x //= 2\n                self.tree[x] = self.query_fn(self.tree[x*2], self.tree[x*2+1])\n                if self.lazy[x] is not None:\n                    self.tree[x] = self.update_fn(self.tree[x], self.lazy[x])\n\n        L += self.N\n        R += self.N\n        L0, R0 = L, R\n        while L <= R:\n            if L & 1:  # is right child\n                self.__apply(L, h)\n                L += 1\n            if R & 1 == 0:  # is left child\n                self.__apply(R, h)\n                R -= 1\n            L //= 2\n            R //= 2\n        pull(L0)\n        pull(R0)\n\n    def query(self, L, R):  # Time: O(logN), Space: O(N)\n        def push(x):\n            n = 2**self.H\n            while n != 1:\n                y = x // n\n                if self.lazy[y] is not None:\n                    self.__apply(y*2, self.lazy[y])\n                    self.__apply(y*2 + 1, self.lazy[y])\n                    self.lazy[y] = None\n                n //= 2\n\n        result = None\n        if L > R:\n            return result\n\n        L += self.N\n        R += self.N\n        push(L)\n        push(R)\n        while L <= R:\n            if L & 1:  # is right child\n                result = self.query_fn(result, self.tree[L])\n                L += 1\n            if R & 1 == 0:  # is left child\n                result = self.query_fn(result, self.tree[R])\n                R -= 1\n            L //= 2\n            R //= 2\n        return result\n    \n    def __str__(self):\n        showList = []\n        for i in xrange(self.N):\n            showList.append(self.query(i, i))\n        return \",\".join(map(str, showList))\n\n\n# competitive programming solution\nclass Solution(object):\n    def minDayskVariants(self, points, k):\n        \"\"\"\n        :type points: List[List[int]]\n        :type k: int\n        :rtype: int\n        \"\"\"\n        def add_rec(rec, intervals):\n            x0, y0, x1, y1 = rec\n            # add [y0, y1] by 1 in [x0, x1+1)\n            intervals.append([[x0,   +1], [y0, y1]])\n            intervals.append([[x1+1, -1], [y0, y1]])\n\n        def check(points, k, l):  # Time: O(nlogn), Space: O(n)\n            intervals = []\n            y_set = set()\n            for x, y in points:\n                add_rec([x-l, y-l, x+l, y+l], intervals)\n                y_set.add(y-l)\n                y_set.add(y+l)\n            intervals.sort()\n            y_to_idx = {y:i for i, y in enumerate(sorted(y_set))}  # coordinate compression\n            st = SegmentTree(len(y_to_idx))\n            for [_, v], [y0, y1] in intervals:  # line sweep\n                st.update(y_to_idx[y0], y_to_idx[y1], v)\n                if st.query(0, len(y_to_idx)-1) >= k:\n                    return True\n            return False\n                \n        points = [[x+y, x-y] for x, y in points]  # rotate\n        min_x = min(points)[0]\n        max_x = max(points)[0]\n        min_y = min(points, key=lambda x: x[1])[1]\n        max_y = max(points, key=lambda x: x[1])[1]\n        left, right = 0, ((max_x-min_x)+(max_y-min_y)+1)//2\n        while left <= right:\n            mid = left + (right-left)//2\n            if check(points, k, mid):\n                right = mid-1\n            else:\n                left = mid+1\n        return left\n\n\n# Time:  O(n^2 * logr), r is the sum of range x size and range y size\n# Space: O(n)\nimport collections\n\n\n# interview solution\nclass Solution2(object):\n    def minDayskVariants(self, points, k):\n        \"\"\"\n        :type points: List[List[int]]\n        :type k: int\n        :rtype: int\n        \"\"\"\n        def add_rec(rec, intervals):\n            x0, y0, x1, y1 = rec\n            # add [y0, y1+1) by 1 in [x0, x1+1)\n            intervals[x0][y0] += 1\n            intervals[x0][y1+1] -= 1\n            intervals[x1+1][y0] -= 1\n            intervals[x1+1][y1+1] += 1\n\n        def check(points, k, l):  # Time: O(n^2), Space: O(n)\n            intervals = collections.defaultdict(lambda:collections.defaultdict(int))\n            y_set = set()\n            for x, y in points:\n                add_rec([x-l, y-l, x+l, y+l], intervals)\n                y_set.add(y-l)\n                y_set.add(y+l+1)\n            sorted_y = sorted(y_set)\n            sorted_x = sorted(intervals.iterkeys())\n            count = collections.Counter()\n            for x in sorted_x:  # line sweep\n                for y, c in intervals[x].iteritems():\n                    count[y] += c\n                cnt = 0\n                for y in sorted_y:\n                    cnt += count[y]\n                    if cnt >= k:\n                        return True\n            return False\n                \n        points = [[x+y, x-y] for x, y in points]  # rotate\n        min_x = min(points)[0]\n        max_x = max(points)[0]\n        min_y = min(points, key=lambda x: x[1])[1]\n        max_y = max(points, key=lambda x: x[1])[1]\n        left, right = 0, ((max_x-min_x)+(max_y-min_y)+1)//2\n        while left <= right:\n            mid = left + (right-left)//2\n            if check(points, k, mid):\n                right = mid-1\n            else:\n                left = mid+1\n        return left\n1f:[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"mt-6 grid lg:grid-cols-[1fr_280px] gap-10\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"article\",null,{\"children\":[[\"$\",\"header\",null,{\"className\":\"space-y-4\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"span\",null,{\"className\":\"text-sm text-muted-foreground tabular-nums\",\"children\":[\"#\",1956]}],[\"$\",\"span\",null,{\"className\":\"inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide bg-hard/15 text-hard\",\"children\":\"Hard\"}],[\"$\",\"span\",null,{\"className\":\"inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide bg-muted text-muted-foreground\",\"children\":\"Premium on LC\"}],[\"$\",\"span\",null,{\"className\":\"inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide border border-border text-muted-foreground\",\"children\":[\"~\",50,\" min\"]}]]}],[\"$\",\"h1\",null,{\"className\":\"text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight\",\"children\":\"Minimum Time For K Virus Variants to Spread\"}],[\"$\",\"p\",null,{\"className\":\"text-muted-foreground max-w-2xl\",\"children\":[\"Time \",[\"$\",\"strong\",null,{\"className\":\"text-foreground\",\"children\":\"O(nlogn * logr)\"}],\" · \",\"Space \",[\"$\",\"strong\",null,{\"className\":\"text-foreground\",\"children\":\"O(n)\"}],\" · \",[\"$\",\"a\",null,{\"href\":\"https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-time-for-k-virus-variants-to-spread/\",\"target\":\"_blank\",\"rel\":\"noopener noreferrer\",\"className\":\"text-primary underline-offset-2 hover:underline\",\"children\":\"Official statement on LeetCode\"}]]}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex flex-wrap gap-2\",\"children\":[[[\"$\",\"$L3\",\"geometry\",{\"href\":\"/topics/geometry\",\"children\":[\"$\",\"span\",null,{\"className\":\"inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide bg-primary/15 text-primary\",\"children\":\"geometry\"}]}]],[[\"$\",\"$L3\",\"binary-search\",{\"href\":\"/patterns/binary-search\",\"children\":[\"$\",\"span\",null,{\"className\":\"inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide border border-border text-muted-foreground\",\"children\":\"binary search\"}]}],[\"$\",\"$L3\",\"segment-tree\",{\"href\":\"/patterns/segment-tree\",\"children\":[\"$\",\"span\",null,{\"className\":\"inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide border border-border text-muted-foreground\",\"children\":\"segment tree\"}]}]],[]]}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex flex-wrap gap-2 pt-1\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"$L20\",null,{\"slug\":\"minimum-time-for-k-virus-variants-to-spread\"}],[[\"$\",\"$L3\",\"cpp\",{\"href\":\"/problems/minimum-time-for-k-virus-variants-to-spread/cpp\",\"className\":\"text-sm text-primary hover:underline\",\"children\":\"cpp\"}],[\"$\",\"$L3\",\"python\",{\"href\":\"/problems/minimum-time-for-k-virus-variants-to-spread/python\",\"className\":\"text-sm text-primary hover:underline\",\"children\":\"python\"}]]]}]]}],[\"$\",\"section\",null,{\"className\":\"mt-10\",\"id\":\"solutions\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h2\",null,{\"className\":\"text-xl font-bold mb-3\",\"children\":\"Solutions\"}],[\"$\",\"$L21\",null,{\"solutions\":{\"cpp\":{\"language\":\"C++\",\"languageSlug\":\"cpp\",\"filename\":\"minimum-time-for-k-virus-variants-to-spread.cpp\",\"code\":\"$22\",\"sourcePath\":\"C++/minimum-time-for-k-virus-variants-to-spread.cpp\"},\"python\":{\"language\":\"Python\",\"languageSlug\":\"python\",\"filename\":\"minimum-time-for-k-virus-variants-to-spread.py\",\"code\":\"$23\",\"sourcePath\":\"Python/minimum-time-for-k-virus-variants-to-spread.py\"}}}]]}],[\"$L24\",\"$L25\",\"$L26\",\"$L27\",\"$L28\",\"$L29\",\"$L2a\",\"$L2b\",\"$L2c\",\"$L2d\"],\"$L2e\",\"$L2f\",\"$L30\",\"$L31\",\"$L32\",\"$L33\"]}],\"$L34\"]}]\n3c:I[203221,[\"/_next/static/chunks/2fvm6eoqeukxu.js\",\"/_next/static/chunks/1ntn7efqc-iiw.js\",\"/_next/static/chunks/0plpm2axnqe9k.js\",\"/_next/static/chunks/259rkrk9l2f9c.js\"],\"ConfidenceTracker\"]\n35:T443,<h2>What is Minimum Time For K Virus Variants to Spread?</h2>\n<p><strong>Minimum Time For K Virus Variants to Spread</strong> (LeetCode #1956) is a <strong>Hard</strong> problem that primarily trains <strong>geometry</strong>.</p>\n<h3>How to think about it</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Restate the goal</strong> in your own words before coding.</li>\n<li>Work a <strong>tiny example</strong> by hand so the invariant becomes obvious.</li>\n<li>Identify the <strong>pattern</strong> — this problem aligns with <strong>binary search and segment tree</strong>.</li>\n<li>Only then translate the idea into code.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Why this problem matters</h3>\n<p>Hard problems force you to combine patterns and prove complexity carefully — interview gold.\nOfficial solution notes mention: Geometry, Binary Search, Line Sweep, Segment Tree.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>AlgoForge explanations are original teaching notes. Always open the <a href=\"https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-time-for-k-virus-variants-to-spread/\">official problem statement on LeetCode</a> for constraints and examples.</p>\n</blockquote>\n24:[\"$\",\"section\",\"beginner\",{\"id\":\"beginner\",\"className\":\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h2\",null,{\"className\":\"text-xl font-bold\",\"children\":\"Beginner Explanation\"}],false]}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"prose-af\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"$35\"}}]]}]\n36:T4e7,<h2>Interview approach for Minimum Time For K Virus Variants to Spread</h2>\n<h3>Opening (30–60 seconds)</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Clarify inputs/outputs and edge cases (empty input, single element, duplicates, overflow).</li>\n<li>State a <strong>brute force</strong> so the interviewer knows you can solve it naively.</li>\n<li>Propose the <strong>optimal direction</strong> tied to <strong>binary search and segment tree</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Core solution narrative</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Define the <strong>state</strong> you track (pointers, DP cell, set membership, stack top, etc.).</li>\n<li>Explain the <strong>transition</strong> when you process the next element.</li>\n<li>Call out <strong>time</strong> (O(nlogn * logr)) and <strong>space</strong> (O(n)) before coding.</li>\n<li>Code cleanly; narrate variable names.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>What interviewers listen for</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Correctness on edge cases</li>\n<li>Complexity honesty</li>\n<li>Ability to discuss <strong>trade-offs</strong> (e.g., hash map space vs. sort + two pointers)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Follow-up questions they may ask</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Can you solve it with less memory?</li>\n<li>What if the input stream is infinite / doesn't fit in RAM?</li>\n<li>How would tests look for adversarial inputs?</li>\n</ul>\n25:[\"$\",\"section\",\"interview\",{\"id\":\"interview\",\"className\":\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h2\",null,{\"className\":\"text-xl font-bold\",\"children\":\"Interview Walkthrough\"}],false]}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"prose-af\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"$36\"}}]]}]\n26:[\"$\",\"section\",\"optimized\",{\"id\":\"optimized\",\"className\":\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h2\",null,{\"className\":\"text-xl font-bold\",\"children\":\"Optimized Approach\"}],false]}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"prose-af\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"<h2>Optimized solution notes</h2>\\n<p>The reference solutions on AlgoForge target <strong>O(nlogn * logr)</strong> time and <strong>O(n)</strong> space.</p>\\n<h3>Pattern focus: binary search and segment tree</h3>\\n<p>Use the pattern as a checklist:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>binary search</strong> — confirm the invariant holds after each step</li>\\n<li><strong>segment tree</strong> — confirm the invariant holds after each step</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Multiple methods appear in the source solutions — compare them and explain when each is preferable.</p>\\n<h3>Implementation tips</h3>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Prefer readable names over micro-optimizations in interviews.</li>\\n<li>Extract helpers only when they clarify (e.g., expand-around-center, DFS visit).</li>\\n<li>After AC-level logic, re-scan for off-by-one and null checks.</li>\\n</ul>\\n\"}}]]}]\n27:[\"$\",\"section\",\"complexity\",{\"id\":\"complexity\",\"className\":\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h2\",null,{\"className\":\"text-xl font-bold\",\"children\":\"Complexity Analysis\"}],false]}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"prose-af\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"<h2>Complexity</h2>\\n<table>\\n<thead>\\n<tr>\\n<th>Measure</th>\\n<th>Bound</th>\\n</tr>\\n</thead>\\n<tbody>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Time</td>\\n<td><strong>O(nlogn * logr)</strong></td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Space</td>\\n<td><strong>O(n)</strong></td>\\n</tr>\\n</tbody>\\n</table>\\n<h3>How to justify this in an interview</h3>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>Time:</strong> count loops, map/set operations, and recursive branching; state average vs worst case if relevant.</li>\\n<li><strong>Space:</strong> include hash maps, recursion stack, and output allocation when the problem asks for it.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>If your implementation differs from the reference, re-derive big-O from <em>your</em> code — never memorize a complexity you cannot defend.</p>\\n\"}}]]}]\n28:[\"$\",\"section\",\"common-mistakes\",{\"id\":\"common-mistakes\",\"className\":\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h2\",null,{\"className\":\"text-xl font-bold\",\"children\":\"Common Mistakes\"}],false]}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"prose-af\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"<h2>Common mistakes on Minimum Time For K Virus Variants to Spread</h2>\\n<ol>\\n<li><strong>Skipping edge cases</strong> — empty collections, single-element inputs, max constraints.</li>\\n<li><strong>Wrong invariant</strong> for binary search and segment tree — updating state too early or too late.</li>\\n<li><strong>Mutating input unexpectedly</strong> when the problem forbids it.</li>\\n<li><strong>Off-by-one</strong> in windows, ranges, or binary search bounds.</li>\\n<li><strong>Ignoring overflow / precision</strong> for integer arithmetic problems.</li>\\n<li><strong>Overengineering</strong> — jumping to an advanced structure when a simpler approach works.</li>\\n</ol>\\n\"}}]]}]\n29:[\"$\",\"section\",\"alternatives\",{\"id\":\"alternatives\",\"className\":\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h2\",null,{\"className\":\"text-xl font-bold\",\"children\":\"Alternative Approaches\"}],false]}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"prose-af\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"<h2>Alternatives</h2>\\n<p>The source file includes more than one method. Compare:</p>\\n<ol>\\n<li><strong>Primary optimized path</strong> — best complexity for typical interviews.</li>\\n<li><strong>Secondary approach</strong> — often brute force, sorting-based, or space-optimized variant.</li>\\n</ol>\\n<p>Practice articulating <strong>when</strong> you would pick each (constraints, readability, follow-ups).</p>\\n\"}}]]}]\n2a:[\"$\",\"section\",\"edge-cases\",{\"id\":\"edge-cases\",\"className\":\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h2\",null,{\"className\":\"text-xl font-bold\",\"children\":\"Edge Cases\"}],false]}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"prose-af\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"<h2>Edge cases checklist</h2>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Minimum input size</li>\\n<li>Maximum input size / time limits</li>\\n<li>Duplicates and already-sorted input</li>\\n<li>Negative numbers / zeros (if applicable)</li>\\n<li>Disconnected structures (graphs/trees)</li>\\n<li>Single path vs branching recursion depth</li>\\n</ul>\\n\"}}]]}]\n2b:[\"$\",\"section\",\"pattern-recognition\",{\"id\":\"pattern-recognition\",\"className\":\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h2\",null,{\"className\":\"text-xl font-bold\",\"children\":\"Pattern Recognition\"}],false]}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"prose-af\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"<h2>Spotting this pattern</h2>\\n<p>Signal phrases that point to <strong>binary search and segment tree</strong>:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Sorted input or ability to sort without changing the answer class</li>\\n<li>Need for contiguous subarray / substring → consider sliding window</li>\\n<li>Need for O(1) membership → hash set/map</li>\\n<li>Optimal substructure + overlapping subproblems → DP</li>\\n<li>Connectivity / components → graph DFS/BFS or Union-Find</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Primary topics: <strong>geometry</strong>.</p>\\n\"}}]]}]\n2c:[\"$\",\"section\",\"follow-ups\",{\"id\":\"follow-ups\",\"className\":\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h2\",null,{\"className\":\"text-xl font-bold\",\"children\":\"Follow-up Interview Questions\"}],false]}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"prose-af\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"<h2>Follow-ups</h2>\\n<ol>\\n<li>How does the solution change if the input is a stream?</li>\\n<li>Can you solve it in-place?</li>\\n<li>What if duplicates must be handled differently?</li>\\n<li>How would you parallelize the approach?</li>\\n<li>Design tests that would break a buggy implementation.</li>\\n</ol>\\n\"}}]]}]\n2d:[\"$\",\"section\",\"practice\",{\"id\":\"practice\",\"className\":\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"h2\",null,{\"className\":\"text-xl font-bold\",\"children\":\"Practice Recommendations\"}],false]}],[\"$\",\"div\",null,{\"className\":\"prose-af\",\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\":{\"__html\":\"<h2>What to practice next</h2>\\n<ol>\\n<li>Re-solve <strong>Minimum Time For K Virus Variants to Spread</strong> in a second language (cpp, python).</li>\\n<li>Drill 3–5 more problems tagged <strong>geometry</strong>.</li>\\n<li>Teach the solution out loud in under 5 minutes.</li>\\n<li>Add this problem to your revision calendar in 3 days and 14 days.</li>\\n</ol>